s fit the guidelines. They are Java files, which could lead to a potential violation. I need to consider whether making public static inner classes in LoadClassTest could resolve these issues, especially after previous coverage concerns. Plus, the report suggests lines were covered post-update.\n../8397-07776246/human-intervention-logs/org.hibernate.validator:hibernate-validator:9.1.0.Final/improve-library-coverage/pi-generation-2026-06-24T11-55-00-552420Z.log:5473:[recv] {\"type\": \"message_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Evaluating class file support**\\n\\nI'm working through whether it's allowed to add support class files without test classes, as per the rule about coverage in dedicated Java test files. We created some contributor classes, but I'm unsure if support files fit the guidelines. They are Java files, which could lead to a potential violation. I need to consider whether making public static inner classes in LoadClassTest could resolve these issues, especially after previous coverage concerns. Plus, the report suggests lines were covered post-update.\\n\\n**Considering class structure**\\n\\nI'm debating whether nested support class binary names are allowed, as the guidelines say not to use \\\"$\\\" in test class or file names. I'm questioning if this applies just to top-level classes or also to inner ones. It looks like support classes could violate the one-to-one rule, but previous attempts indicated they covered non-HV lines. I’m thinking about moving support classes as public static nested ones in LoadClassTest, even with names containing \\\"$\\\" in the metadata.\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_0c53adcb8df17cf9016a3bc89f2bfc81959af0b474f4809d0c\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"content\\\":[],\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABqO8ivOUEjCfQYY7g19OMqOaOt8f28fdtNAgzYEYSci6uIekMCCXBD-wMG5qpYf2d_drRUIji-b2Nb_y-mubqP776bihCS-tfmE8eG-lPEchgNtE7h0Hk-jYCPUij-2Ixk